	<text xml:lang="en">
		<body>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><p>Upon contact with CH4, again a partial reduction is observed, suggesting that reactivity on oxidized Cu species could have occurred. Finally, during steam assisted extraction, Cu returned mostly to the 2+ state, closing the redox cycle. A small trace of methanol was detected in the product stream by mass spectroscopy. Finally, all investigated samples remained crystalline over the whole protocol, accounting on the renown robustness of the UiO-6X frameworks. These results allowed us to verify the potential of novel Cu-MOFs catalysts in DMTM, and helped us in designing the next generation of materials, as foreseen in the ERC-SyG "CUBE" project <ref type="bibr" target="#b3">[3]</ref>.</p></div><figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_0"><head>Figure 1 .</head><label>1</label><figDesc>Figure 1. Evolution of XANES spectra of UiO-66-his-Cu during heating in He (left) and upon dosage of O2 at 150 °C (right).</figDesc><graphic coords="2,34.00,50.65,533.00,225.60" type="bitmap" /></figure>
